1 other political subdivision of this state, and any self-funded multiple employer welfare arrangement that is not
2 regulated by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, 29 U.S.C. 1001, et seq.
3 (6) This section does not apply to disability income, hospital indemnity, medicare supplement,
4 accident-only, vision, dental, specific disease, or long-term care policies.
5 (7) As used in this section, the following definitions apply:
6 (a) "Amplification device" means a hearing device, hearing aid, or wearable, nondisposable,
7 nonexperimental instrument or device designed to aid or compensate for impaired human hearing and any
8 parts, attachments, or accessories for the instrument or device, including an ear mold but excluding batteries
9 and cords.
10 (b) "Generally accepted standards of medical practice" means standards that are based on
11 credible scientific evidence published in peer-reviewed medical literature generally recognized by the relevant
12 medical community, physician specialty society recommendations, the view of physicians practicing in relevant
13 clinical areas, and any other relevant factors.
14 (c) "Health care provider" means an individual licensed under Title 37, chapter 3, 15, or 20. A
15 nurse practitioner licensed under Title 37, chapter 8, also is a health care provider for the purposes of this
16 section.
17 (d) "Hearing loss" means a disruption in the normal hearing process that may occur in the outer,
18 middle, or inner ear, whereby sound waves are not converted to electrical signals and nerve impulses are not
19 transmitted to the brain to be interpreted.
20 (e) "Medical necessity" means health care services that a physician, exercising prudent clinical
21 judgment, would provide to a patient for the purpose of preventing, evaluating, diagnosing, or treating an
22 illness, injury, disease, or its symptoms, and that are:
23 (i) in accordance with generally accepted standards of medical practice;
24 (ii) clinically appropriate, in terms of type, frequency, extent, site, and duration, and considered
25 effective for the patient's illness, injury, or disease;
26 (iii) not primarily for the convenience of the patient, physician, or other health care provider; and
27 (iv) not more costly than an alternative service or sequence of services at least as likely to produce
28 equivalent therapeutic or diagnostic results as to the diagnosis or treatment of that patient's illness, injury, or
